    "summary": "Greek red-figure pottery (c. 530–300 BC) was the revolutionary ceramic painting technique invented in Athens around 530 BC — a reversal of the black-figure method, leaving figures in the natural red-orange color of the clay while painting the background black. This inversion allowed painters to use a brush rather than an incising tool for detail work, enabling the depiction of foreshortening, musculature, facial expression, and spatial depth in ways impossible with incised lines.\n\nThe 'red-figure revolution' allowed Greek painters to achieve unprecedented naturalism and compositional sophistication. Masters of the technique like Euphronios (whose krater depicting the death of Sarpedon is one of the most admired surviving works), the Berlin Painter, and the Brygos Painter created paintings whose skill approaches the finest Greek sculpture. Red-figure pottery dominated Greek ceramic production for two centuries and was exported across the Mediterranean world. The scenes depicted range from mythology (symposia of the gods, Dionysiac revelries, heroic combat) to daily Athenian life (music lessons, athletic training, erotic scenes from symposia). The technique's ability to render the human figure naturalistically makes red-figure pottery the primary visual record of how ancient Greeks represented themselves and their world.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red-figure_pottery",
